{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491291","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491291"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:41:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:41:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"905"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"905","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/905"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.12,0.11,0.18,0.58]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"905"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109043"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"905","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/905"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"905"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91409"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"175"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1130"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1201"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14276"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39483"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40711"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109043","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109043"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 60-year-old man is taken to the Emergency Department following an unwitnessed, unconscious collapse. He has been unwell for the last four days with diarrhoea, abdominal discomfort, and poor oral intake. On examination his pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 100/60mmHg, and respiratory rate 22/min. His overall condition improves considerable after intravenous fluid resuscitation. A bedside ultrasound is performed and shows a previously undiagnosed 50mm abdominal aortic aneurysm (AAA), with no evidence of leakage or rupture. There is no free peritoneal fluid. No other abnormalities are found. Two hours later the patient feels well, with a blood pressure of 126/84 mmHg and pulse 90/min.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management of the AAA?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Plain abdominal X-ray","Urgent CT abdomen","Angiography","Surgical repair","Outpatient follow-up"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis abdominal aortic aneurysm (AAA) is an incidental finding and unrelated to the patient\u0027s current illness. It does not need any further immediate assessment or intervention. Even if further imaging was considered, a \u003Cstrong\u003Eplain abdominal X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E is an inappropriate tool for the assessment of soft issue structures. A \u003Cstrong\u003ECT scan\u003C/strong\u003E \u00b1 \u003Cstrong\u003Eangiography\u003C/strong\u003E are useful tools in the pre-surgical evaluation of AAA, however in an asymptomatic case of AAA, CT is not needed. A CT scan in this setting would only be indicated if needed for the assessment of his presenting symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough there is variation in the international guidelines for the surveillance of asymptomatic abdominal aortic aneurysms (AAAs), the 2024 European Society for Vascular Surgery (ESVS) guidelines are most widely followed, including in Australia and New Zealand. The ESVS guidelines recommend the following monitoring schedule for asymptomatic patients according to AAA diameter:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E25 - 29 mm: ultrasound every five years\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E30 - 39 mm: ultrasound every three years\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E40 - 49 mm (men) or 40 \u2013 44 mm (women): annual ultrasound\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u226550 mm (men)\u003C/strong\u003E or \u226545 mm (women):\u003Cstrong\u003E ultrasound every six months \u003C/strong\u003E(this would be appropriate for this case)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u226555 mm (men) or \u226550 mm (women): most surgeons would consider offering \u003Cstrong\u003Esurgical repair; \u003C/strong\u003Enote that the threshold for elective repair in women is lower due to higher rupture risk at smaller diameters.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to note that these are general guidelines, and different monitoring protocols may be utilised for patients with AAAs based on clinician judgement and patient factors (e.g. life expectancy, suitability for future repair, patient preferences).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Abdominal aortic aneurysms \u003C55 mm diameter in men require regular surveillance."],"references":["ESVS 2024 Clinical Practice Guidelines on the Management of Abdominal Aortic Aneurysm. In: European Society for Vascular Surgery (ESVS) [online]. Accessed 2025 Jun 25. Available at: https://esvs.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/ESVS-2024-AAA-Guidelines.pdf","Kent KC. Abdominal Aortic Aneurysms. N Engl J Med 2014; 371:2101-8.","Robinson D, Mees B, Verhagen H, Chuen J. Aortic aneurysms Screening, surveillance and referral. Australian Family Physician. 2013;42:364-9.","Aortic aneurysm [Internet]. Melbourne (VIC). Australian and New Zealand society for vascular surgery. [cited 2021 Jan 20]. Available from: https://www.anzsvs.org.au/patient-information/aortic-aneurysm/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91409"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"905"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91409","links"